Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9. Boil a full #kettle{} for the potatoes.

Remove the @British beef roasting joint{400%g} from your fridge to allow it come up to room
temperature. Pour enough oil into a deep #baking tray{} to cover the bottom and pop into the
oven. Peel and chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 3cm chunks.

Pour the boiled water into a large #saucepan{} on high heat with @salt{1/2%tsp}. Boil the
potatoes for ~{5-6%mins} or until the edges are soft.

Meanwhile, trim the @carrot{2}, then halve lengthways (no need to peel). Chop into roughly
1cm wide, 5cm long batons. Peel and grate the @garlic clove{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

When the potatoes are ready, drain in a #colander{} and sprinkle over the @plain flour{1%tbsp}.
Shake to fluff them up, then carefully add them to the hot baking tray, gently turning in
the oil.

Season with the @dried rosemary{1}, @salt{} and @pepper{}, then roast on the top shelf until
golden, ~{30-35%mins}. Turn halfway through.

Meanwhile, pop the @panko breadcrumbs{10%g} into a small #bowl{}. Add the
@olive oil{1/2%tbsp}(for the crumb), season with salt and pepper, then mix to combine.

Transfer the beef to a baking tray. Drizzle with @olive oil{} and season generously with
salt and pepper. Spread the @Dijon mustard{10%g} over the top of the beef and spoon the
breadcrumbs on top. Press it down with a #spoon{}. > Wash your hands and equipment after
handling raw meat.

Add the carrots to the same tray. Drizzle with oil, season with salt and pepper, then toss
to coat. TIP: Use another tray if needed.

Roast on the middle shelf of your oven for ~{20-25%mins} ~{30-35%mins} (depending on size)
for medium-rare. Add an extra ~{5%mins} if you like your beef more well done.

Meanwhile, wipe out the (now empty) potato pan. Pour the @water{300%ml}(for the jus) into
the pan and bring to the boil on high heat.

Stir in the @red wine jus paste{30%g}, then reduce the heat to medium-high. Allow the sauce
to bubble and thicken, stirring regularly, ~{10-12%mins}. Set aside.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of @olive oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @British smoked bacon lardons{60%g}. Stir-fry until golden, ~{4-5%mins}.
> Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw meat. Cook bacon thoroughly.

Add the @sliced spring greens{150%g} and @water{1%tbsp}(for the greens) to the bacon.
Cover with a tight-fitting #lid{} and cook until wilted, ~{5-6%mins}.

Add the @garlic{1%clove}(grated) and cook for ~{1%min} more. Season with salt and pepper.

When the beef is ready, transfer it to a #cutting board{} to rest, wrapped loosely in
#foil{}, for at least ~{10%mins} before slicing. > The beef is safe to eat when browned on
the outside.

Meanwhile, drizzle the @honey{1%tsp} over the carrots and return to the oven roast for
a further ~{5%mins}.

When everything's ready, reheat the red wine jus if needed. Thinly slice the beef and share
between your plates.

Serve the roast potatoes, honey glazed carrots and bacon spring greens alongside.

Drizzle over the red wine jus to finish. Enjoy!